Perfect — great to hear the colors and basic structure are working! That means Step 1 is solid. Now we can focus on Step 2: Layout Structure, which is about making all pages consistent, responsive, and properly wrapped, just like in your Next.js app.


---

Step 2: Layout Structure for React + Vite

In your Next.js app, the structure likely comes from:

app/layout.tsx → wraps pages in header, sidebar, main content area, footer

components/sidebar.tsx → the left-hand navigation

components/ui/* → reusable containers, cards, tables, buttons


We’ll replicate that in Vite.


---

A. Create a Layout Component

File: src/components/Layout.tsx

import { ReactNode } from "react";
import Sidebar from "./Sidebar";

interface LayoutProps {
  children: ReactNode;
}

export default function Layout({ children }: LayoutProps) {
  return (
    <div className="flex min-h-screen bg-background text-darkText">
      {/* Sidebar */}
      <Sidebar className="w-64 min-h-screen bg-[#1a1a1a] shadow-lg" />

      {/* Main content */}
      <div className="flex-1 flex flex-col">
        {/* Header */}
        <header className="p-4 bg-[#1a1a1a] shadow-md text-primary font-bold">
          WAutomator
        </header>

        {/* Page content */}
        <main className="flex-1 p-6 overflow-auto">{children}</main>

        {/* Footer */}
        <footer className="p-4 bg-[#1a1a1a] text-sm text-gray-400 text-center">
          © 2025 WAutomator
        </footer>
      </div>
    </div>
  );
}

Explanation:

Top-level div uses flex row → sidebar + main content.

Sidebar is fixed width (w-64) and full height.

Main content uses flex-col for header → main → footer.

main scrolls independently (overflow-auto).

Colors come from your Tailwind/global theme.



---

B. Create Sidebar Component

File: src/components/Sidebar.tsx

import { NavLink } from "react-router-dom"; // or simple <a> links

export default function Sidebar({ className = "" }: { className?: string }) {
  const links = [
    { name: "Connect", to: "/connect" },
    { name: "Leads", to: "/leads" },
    { name: "Broadcast", to: "/broadcast" },
    { name: "Templates", to: "/templates" },
    { name: "Settings", to: "/settings" },
  ];

  return (
    <nav className={`flex flex-col p-4 space-y-4 ${className}`}>
      {links.map((link) => (
        <NavLink
          key={link.to}
          to={link.to}
          className={({ isActive }) =>
            `block px-4 py-2 rounded hover:bg-primary hover:text-darkText ${
              isActive ? "bg-primary text-darkText" : ""
            }`
          }
        >
          {link.name}
        </NavLink>
      ))}
    </nav>
  );
}

Notes:

Uses Tailwind spacing (p-4, space-y-4) and hover effects.

Highlights the active page.

Works with React Router — if you don’t use it, replace NavLink with <a href="#">.



---

C. Wrap Pages in Layout

For example, your Connect.tsx:

import Layout from "../components/Layout";
import QRCodeComponent from "../components/QRCodeComponent";

export default function Connect() {
  return (
    <Layout>
      <div className="flex flex-col items-center justify-center h-full">
        <h1 className="text-3xl font-bold mb-6 text-primary">Connect WhatsApp</h1>
        <QRCodeComponent className="mb-4" />
        <button className="bg-primary text-darkText px-6 py-2 rounded hover:bg-secondary transition">
          Connect
        </button>
      </div>
    </Layout>
  );
}

All pages will now have consistent sidebar, header, footer, and padding.

Layout is responsive if you add Tailwind responsive classes later (md:w-64, sm:hidden, etc.).



---

Next Steps After Layout

1. Wrap all pages (Leads, Broadcast, Templates, Settings) in this Layout.


2. Update Sidebar links to match your Vite routes.


3. Start styling UI components (buttons, tables, cards) using Tailwind from components/ui/*.




